<article class="h-entry">
    <h3 class="p-name">If we're going to count, count.</h3>
    <p class="p-summary">A simple fix for carbon offset systems: count the carbon.</p>
    <p class="p-byline">Published by <a class="p-author h-card" href="/">Sam Butler</a>
       <!-- on <time class="dt-published" datetime="2013-06-13 12:00:00">13<sup>th</sup> June 2013</time></p> -->    
    <div class="e-content">
        <p>I presume you've read the news.</p>

        <p>By and large, most carbon offsets to date — even the best of them — <a href="https://carbon-direct.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/CD-Commentary-on-Voluntary-Registry-Offsets-Database_April-2021.pdf">are basically bullshit. <img src="" style="display: none;"/></a></p>
        
        <!-- <p>And yet, because we have not yet gathered the social muster to force a more prudent and sane course of action to avoiding environmental collapse (like, the decisionmakers at polluting firms deciding to ... stop polluting), it appears politicians and industry chiefs and great Bankers around the world are set on a new messiah, a new boss: carbon offset regimes.</p> -->
        
        <p>And yet, because we have not yet gathered the social muster to force a more prudent and sane course of action to avoid environmental collapse (like, the decisionmakers at polluting firms deciding to ... stop polluting), it appears politicians and industry chiefs and great leaders around the world are set on a new messiah, a new boss: carbon offset regimes.</p>
        
        <p>At this point, we must answer a pivotal question, which should guide all our future thought and actions.</p>
        
        <h4>What are we trying to do?</h4>
        
        <p>When you say "climate", or I say "sustainability", what are we trying to do?</p>
        
        <p>For me, I'd sum it up as:</p>
        
        <strong>Avoid environmental collapse, and improve social outcomes.</strong>
        
        <p>This begs a second question:</p>
            
            <strong>Why is the environment collapsing?</strong>
        
        <p>In short, because our ways of life are too burdensome on the environment.</p>
        
        <p>Ex: If our environment had a greater carrying capacity, or our ways of life were less burdensome, the environment would not be collapsing.</p>
        
            <p>... But right now, it is.</p>
        
        <!-- <p>To avoid environmental collapse, we must shift to ways of life that are <em>less burdensome</em> on the environment (reduce / reuse / repair / recycle),  and which <em>increase the carrying capacity</em> of the environment (regenerate), while improving social outcomes.</p>
        
        <p>Burdens include activities like overharvesting, polluting, and mining.  Increasing carrying capacity include reforestation, regenerative agriculture, rewilding, re-everything.</p> -->
        
        <p>And one of the biggest burdens on the environment is carbon in the atmosphere.</p>
        
        <p>How?</p>
        
        <p>1. Excessive absorption of CO2 is killing ocean life (by reducing PH levels and making the water acidic).</p>
        
        <p>2. Excessive GHG in the atmosphere is reducing insect fertility, driving species extinction, destabilizing weather patterns, increasing rates of natural disasters, and simultaneously creating flood and drought risks (by heating the atmosphere at a rate of 4 nuclear bombs per second, h/t <a href="https://continuations.com/post/187534394205/climate-crisis">Albert Wenger</a>), along with diminishing global food productivity.</p>
        
        <p>Better yet, these consequences are happening faster and faster every day.</p>
        
        <p>The more heat trapped in the atmosphere → the more heat trapped in the atmosphere → the more heat trapped in the atmosphere.  (Maybe we'll get some luck with increasing heat causing increasing cloudcover and albedo reflection.  Don't count on it.)</p>
        
        <p>To slow down this rollercoaster of a not-so-idyllic future, and remove this existential burden from our environment, we need to permanently decrease the amount of carbon and GHGs that are in the atmosphere.</p>
        
        <p>How much?</p>
        
        <p>Enough to maintain a maximum of ~350 parts per million CO2.</p>
            
        <p>We were last at 350 ppm <a href="https://keelingcurve.ucsd.edu/">in 1987</a>, so that means we need to remove all of the carbon put into the atmosphere over the last 34 years, and all of the new of the carbon we emit while we clean up the mess behind us.</p>
        
        <p>So when it's all said and done, we'll have removed 64 years of carbon emitted during the peak oil period of human civilization.</p>
        
        <!-- <p>If we had 5 rings and were in a Marvel movie, maybe we could do this in a snap.</p>
        
        <p>Unfortunately, this will be much more difficult here in our universe.</p> -->

        <p><em>(pause)</em></p>
        
        <p>On the bright side, our environment is capable of permanently removing carbon from the atmosphere.  Also, human inventions are becoming more and more capable of permanently removing carbon from the atmosphere.</p>
        
        <p>So, if we just (a) stop putting carbon into the atmosphere in the first place, (b) increase the Earth's capacity to remove carbon, and (c) rapidly iterate + evolve our human techniques for removing carbon from the atmosphere, we have a plan that is as good as we can muster. (See <a href="https://globalecoguy.org/we-need-4-waves-of-climate-solutions-6e58adbc5ad6">4 Waves of Climate Action</a> by Dr. Jonathan Foley)</p>
        
        <p>And then, we just have to move as fast as concievably possible on removing those 64 years worth of peak oil emissions.</p>
        
        <p>One idea for moving fast is <strong>carbon offsets</strong>.</p>
        
        <p>The purpose of a carbon offset is to offset/counteract/nullify a previous carbon emission — in effect, returning atmospheric carbon levels to a point before your emission took place, such that for the purposes of counting carbon in the atmosphere, your original emission never took place.</p>
        
        <p>This leaves us only with an opportunity cost, of the time and energy spent in going out to fetch your emission, instead of you just not emitting in the first place.</p>
        
        <p>To emphasize: It's way simpler for you, and way better for your future (and everyone else's), to just stop emitting in the first place.</p>
        
        <p>Invest your R&D into ending your emissions before they happen, not running around with a butterfly catcher trying to fetch them back later.  (And if you eliminate your emissions, you don't have to buy any more carbon offsets, because you have no more emissions to offset!)</p>
        
        <p>Maybe enough people reading this will actually start the wheels of industry turning in that direction.  If you do, congratulations!  You've made the rest of this article irrelevant, and I hope that becomes the case.</p>
        
        <p>In the case that carbon offsets remain a thing, well, as the title says:</p>
            
        <h4>If we're going to count, count.</h4>
        
        <p>As you know, pulling carbon out of the atmosphere — only for it to return to the atmosphere — doesn't accomplish anything.</p>
            
        <p>It's like digging a hole in a circle, where every shovelfull ahead of you refills the hole behind you — except, perhaps, you get incrementally better at your technique for temporary displacement.</p>
        
        <p>A pure waste of time, energy, and resources.</p>
        
        <p>So consider this real-world (and ever more common) scenario:</p>
        
        <ul>
            <li>Five years ago, you emitted 100 tons of GHG.</li>
            <li>Instead of reducing your emissions in the first place, you decided to plant 150 of acres of trees, to fetch your emissions after the fact.</li>
            <li>Congratulations!  As of yesterday, the trees you planted removed 100 tons of carbon from the atmosphere.  You have reduced atmospheric carbon levels enough to offset your original 100 tons of emissions — and it only took planting 100,000 trees.</li>
            <li>Now, it's like those 100 tons were never even emitted, leaving us with nothing in the air but the opportunity cost of running around with a butterfly catcher for 5 years, instead of just addressing the problem at the source.</li>
        </ul>
        
        <p>After all of that ...</p>
        
        <p>Today, you wake up to all 100,000 of your trees burning up in a forest fire, releasing all 100 tons of carbon back into the atmosphere.</p>
        
        <p>Now, it’s like those 100 tons were never even <em>removed</em> in the first place (and you just spent 5 years running around with a butterfly catcher.)</p>
        
        <!-- Five years ago, you emitted 100 tons of GHG.
        - You plant enough trees to pull 100 tons of GHG out of the atmosphere by yesterday.
        - Yay!  You have reduced atmospheric GHG levels enough to offset your original 100 tons of emissions.  Now, it’s like those 100 tons were never even emitted, leaving us with nothing in the air but the opportunity cost of running around with a butterfly catcher for 5 years.
        
