        <p>Now, it’s like those 100 tons were never pulled out of the atmosphere (and you wasted 5 years of time, energy, and resources).</p> -->
        
        <p>Question:</p>
        
        <strong>Are your 100 emissions still offset?</strong>
        
        <p><em>In reality?</em>  Obviously not.  Those emissions are still in the atmosphere.</p>
        
        <p><em>In the world of carbon offsets?</em></p>
        
        <p>Why is that a seperate question?</p>
            
        <p>Why is the world of carbon offsets different from reality?</p>
        
        <!-- <p>In part, because the people who make "carbon offsets" into things that polluters can buy for money, tend to think of carbon pulled out of the atmosphere as a "credit."  (As in, "carbon credits.")</p> -->
        
        <p>Because the people and organizations and regulators who make "carbon offsets" into things that polluters can buy, tend to regard carbon pulled out of the atmosphere as a "credit."  (As in, <em>"carbon credits".</em>)</p>
        
        <p>This worldview considers removed carbon <strong>credited</strong> on arrival.  Debt paid.  A sum received.
        
        <p>Once the carbon has been pulled from the atmosphere, the polluter's initial emission is offset.  There is nothing more to do.  It is as though the original emission never took place.</p>
        
            <p>This perspective contains an obvious error:</p>
                
                <p>Carbon removed can return to the atmosphere, such that the original <em>removal</em> never took place, and we are back to square one with the original emission.</p>
        
            <p>The idea of removed carbon as "credits" is a fundamental error, and as a result, the systems built on it are broken on first principles.</p>
        
        <p>Crediting removed carbon on arrival — and ignoring the long-term outcome of that removed carbon — literally incentivizes removal <em>without permanence</em>.</p>
        
        <p>Since permanent removal is more difficult to achieve, less permanent offsets are cheaper to produce and sell.</p>
        
        <p>Since impermanent removal is cheaper, impermanent removal is incentivized.</p>
            
        <p>Since impermanent removal is incentivized, impermanent removal is a likely outcome.</p>
            
        <p>And impermanent removal leads us back to ...</p>
        
        <blockquote>
        
            <p>1. Excessive absorption of CO2 is killing ocean life (by reducing PH levels and making the water acidic).</p>
        
            <p>2. Excessive GHG in the atmosphere is reducing insect fertility, driving species extinction, destabilizing weather patterns, increasing rates of natural disasters, and simultaneously creating flood and drought risks (by heating the atmosphere at a rate of 4 nuclear bombs per second, h/t Albert Wenger), along with diminishing global food productivity.</p>
                        
            <p>The more heat trapped in the atmosphere → the more heat trapped in the atmosphere → the more heat trapped in the atmosphere ...</p>
        
        </blockquote>
        
        <p>Let's revisit an important question:</p>
        
        <h4>What are we trying to do?</h4>
        
        <p>Avoid environment collapse, and improve social outcomes, by lessening burdens, and increasing the environment's carrying capacity.</p>
        
        <p>Today's carbon offset systems don't necessarily contribute to any of those outcomes.</p>
        
        <p>Today's carbon offset systems generate credits, which don't necessarily accomplish anything — and in some cases, worse than nothing, they can actually help firms delay <em>reducing emissions.</em></p>
        
        <p>So if we resist the path of least resistance and decide, instead of stopping emissions before they occur, to try running around with a butterfly catcher for the next 30 years — how can we ensure that our carbon offset systems actually support <strong>what we're trying to do?</strong></p>
        
        <p>Count.</p>
        
        <p>It's that simple.</p>
        
        <p>When a company buys a carbon offset from a carbon removal project, and the project successfully removes carbon, that removed carbon is not "credited" or "recieved" or past-tense at all.</p>
        
        <p>That removed carbon is a dynamic, freeflowing chemical compound, which can return to the atmosphere at any time.</p>
        
        <p>And obviously, if removed carbon returns to the atmosphere, it is no longer <em>removed</em> carbon — so it no longer counts as removed carbon if words have any meaning, and if it's no longer removed carbon, it no longer offsets any prior emissions.</p>
            
            <!-- which is counted <em>in the moment</em> for how much carbon it actually contains, at any given time.</p> -->
        
        <!-- diagram of the vertical bar graph stack, and the horizontal line graph where they fill the curve (going above the curve or under the curve) -->
        
        <!-- <p>If a carbon offset burns up in a pile of smoke, or was nothing more than smoke to begin with, it is counted as such.</p> -->
        
        <p>So if an entity had purchased that no-longer-removed carbon, the no-longer-removed carbon would no longer offset any of the entity's past emissions.</p>
        
        <p>When carbon buyers know that removed carbon will be <em>counted</em> in the long-term (instead of "credited" on arrival), that will create <em>accountability</em> in the system.</p>
        
        <p>Accountability could lead to a variety of new behaviors, generally aligned with the goal of <strong>long-term carbon removal:</strong></p>
        
        <ul>
            <li><p>Since permanent carbon removal projects are the least risky (the most likely to be counted as removed carbon, for the longest period of time), they will have the highest demand, and fetch the highest values in the market.</p></li>
            <li><p>It could be so expensive, that many companies could likely choose to swallow the medicine of a better future — and actually invest in stopping their emissions at the source!</p>
            <p>^ This is exactly what we want carbon offsets to do!</p>
            </li>
            <li><p>And if companies decide to buy cheaper carbon removal from impermanent projects, they will do so knowing their investment is ... impermanent.  Risky.</p></li>
            <li><p>Perhaps it could make them "net-zero" for a few years.  But once that removed carbon goes back into the atmosphere, those companies know it will be <strong>counted</strong> as such.  Thus, they know they will be <strong>accountable</strong> for that outcome — and they know they'll have to remove more carbon in a few year's time.</p></li>
        </ul> 
        
