        <p>By <strong>counting</strong> carbon, we can even arrive at a more legitimate role for <em>impermanent</em> carbon removal.</p>
            
        <p>Some carbon buyers could choose to invest in short-term, impermanent carbon removal — with the idea that it could <em>buy them time</em> until more permanent carbon removal is more available and less costly.</p>
        
        <p>There is no illusion.  These buyers know they will have to buy more carbon down the road.  But, perhaps in the meantime, they can invest further into eliminating their own emissions.</p>
        
        <p>So even though they'd have to buy more carbon once the impermanent carbon releases back into the atmosphere, they will have fewer emissions to emit in the long-term.</p>
        
        <p>Exactly what we're aiming for.</p>
        
        <p>This is only a strategy with the possibility of integrity — and not an outright gimmick/scam — if the carbon is <strong>counted</strong>, so buyers are <strong>accountable.</strong></p>
        
        <!-- <p>This is only a strategy with the possibility of integrity, and not an outright gimmick/scam, if <em>the carbon is actually counted.</em></p> -->
        
